#   GET-023: `be get '?#<sha>...'` (trailing dots) silently resolves to the PARENT, not the sha

A ref with trailing dots â€” `?#<sha>...` â€” resolves to the commit's PARENT instead of
`<sha>` (or a clean error). The `...` is read as range/ellipsis syntax and the
resolver lands on the wrong commit SILENTLY. It bit the BLAME-006b land worker: a
`be get '?#3dc19b0a...'` (meant to check out `3dc19b0a`) reverted the worktree to the
parent `f6bea1c5` and dropped a merge hunk, forcing a hand-recovery. A trailing-dots
ref must resolve to `<sha>` or fail loudly â€” never silently pick the parent. Method:
[Issues].

##  Input

### Context
 -  Repro: `be get '?#<sha>...'` (literal trailing `.`/`..`/`...`) â†’ the worktree cur
    becomes the sha's PARENT, not `<sha>`. Observed `be get '?#3dc19b0a...'` â†’
    `f6bea1c5` (3dc19b0a's parent). No error; exit 0.
 -  Likely cause: the `#fragment` `<sha>...` is parsed as a git-style range
    (`A...B` symmetric-difference / `A...` against an implicit endpoint), and the
    resolver picks the merge-base / parent endpoint instead of treating the leading
    40-hex as the target. Resolution path: `REFSResolve` (`keeper/REFS.c:467`) /
    `keeper/RESOLVE.c` (the `#hex` â†’ 40-hex decode). A 40-hex followed by `...` should
    not be a range with an empty/implicit side.
 -  Severity: silent wrong-checkout is dangerous â€” it reverted real work (caught only
    because the worker verified the tree). Pairs with the GET-021 stale-worktree class
    (a wrong cur with no warning).

### Goals
 -  **SAFEGUARD (the core fix):** the ref resolver CLASSIFIES the target as (valid
    sha | valid hashlet-prefix | known branch). If it matches NONE of those, it
    REFUSES with a clear error â€” it MUST NEVER silently fall through to a parent /
    merge-base / nearest-prefix / no-op resolution. `?#<sha>...` is one instance: the
    trailing `...` makes it neither a valid sha nor a branch â†’ reject, don't guess.
 -  `be get '?#<sha>...'` then either resolves to `<sha>` (if trailing dots are
    explicitly stripped as a tolerated form) OR errors â€” but NEVER lands on the parent.
 -  A genuine `A...B` / `A..B` range, if supported, resolves to the documented endpoints;
    a malformed/one-sided range errors rather than guessing.

### Constraints
 -  Fix in the ref-resolution / URI-fragment parse (`keeper/REFS.c` / `RESOLVE.c` /
    the canon query parse), not by special-casing `be get`. Don't regress valid
    hashlet / branch / `?#<sha>` resolution. Add table cases: `?#<sha>`, `?#<sha>.`,
    `?#<sha>...`, plus any real range form.

##  WIP

### Design decisions
 -  ROOT CAUSE (2026-06-16): `be get '?#<sha>'` carries an EMPTY query + a `#fragment`,
    but `sniff/GET.c::SNIFFGetURI` (~`:2067`) only read the QUERY â€” the empty `?`
    matched the trunk row and the `#fragment` was SILENTLY DROPPED (landing on the
    trunk tip, not the sha). A trailing-dots `?#<sha>...` additionally mis-decoded via
    `WHIFFHexHashlet60` (ignored the non-hex tail â†’ wrong object). [The trailing-dots
    *query* form `?<sha>...` was already rejected on trunk by `REFSResolveURI`'s
    `HEXu8sValid` gate â€” the bug is the *fragment* form.]
 -  FIX: a classify-or-reject arm at `sniff/GET.c:2069` â€”
    `if (has_q && $empty(query) && !$empty(fragment))` classify the fragment as
    full-sha (`DOGIsFullSha`) or hashlet (`DOGIsHashlet`) â†’ `GETCheckout`, else REFUSE
    (`SNIFFFAIL`); plus the shared-resolver guard `keeper/KEEP.c:1908`
    (`KEEPResolveTree`, `KEEPFAIL`). Reused existing error codes (no hand-rolled ron60).
 -  REFINED (maintainer): the first cut added a `frag_is_spoilt_hex` helper in
    `graf/LOG.c` with a `hexrun>=6 && <len` "botched-sha" heuristic â€” a MISNOMER (a
    fragment is valid hex or not; the heuristic also false-positived a `#msg-search`
    starting with â‰Ą6 hex). REMOVED it: `GRAFResolveTip` now does the clean binary â€”
    `KEEPResolveRef` resolves it (sha/hashlet/branch) â†’ object selector; else the only
    legit non-object form is a `#<N>`/`#Ln` COUNT (`HUNKu8sFragSplit != 0`, load-bearing
    so counts aren't refused); anything else returns the resolver's miss (refuse). So
    `log:?#<sha>...` â†’ `RESLVNONE` (no silent trunk-log), `#msg-search` is a separate verb
    path (`graf_head_msg_search`), counts still resolve+cap.

